	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Jun 21st 7:37 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Yeah, that bandage drain is tough at lower levels, but it's worth it.&nbsp;&nbsp;Options:<br><br>Take up tailoring -- two spiderling silks equals one silk thread.  Two silk threads = one free bandage.  Pretty low trivial too, so not that hard to accomplish.<br><br>Make friends with a Mage or two (or group with mages), and try to get summoned bandages at the start of each session.  Most mages I know LOVE to summon stuff -- it's part of the fun of playing that class.  A lot of higher level mages hanging around the tunnel are probably more than happy to summon you some bandages and throwing daggers (for pulling).  Don't be a pest, but if you ask one nicely, you'll probably get some.<br><br>You might also try asking a higher level monk for bandages.  Most times I despise beggars, because all they want is Phat Lewtz or a bunch of PP and aren't even polite about it.  However, if a young monk asked for bandages ... well, that would be impossible for me to refuse, having struggled for bandage money myself.  I always carry bandages around and he'd have a couple stacks right away.  I've never been asked for bandages, by the way -- guess the newbies smart enough to want them are too busy trying hard on their own to ask.<br><br>If you have a bunch of extra summoned bandages at the end of a session, try to use them up, as they are NO RENT.  One way to do this is to go to lavastorm (be careful going through Nek) and take a lava bath.  Just go into one of the many lava pools a short way so you don't die getting out.  You'll be at 1 bubble health in no time -- bandage and repeat.<br><br>Just some ideas on working with Bind.<br>&nbsp;<br>Osano<br>Level 44 Human Monk<br>Tholuxe-Paells</td></tr>
